<font color="#FF0000">WARNING SHOTS TO CHILDREN</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jul 17 20:34:57 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
To Joe A.<br><br>
Glad you dropped by. Your contribution is enlightening. Even if you enjoy seeing an old commie exercise in leotards. Do not mind Tom too much, we have had a running battle on rules of engagement and shooting at gooks at early dusk. <br><br>
Shortly before I left Nam in the summer of 68, I captured an old men near our wire that was out there pass curfew just off hill 65. He was walking alongside our perimeter wire. Someone I found out later had not fired a warning shot at him earlier that day. In his shirt was a complete map of our bunkers and artillery positions. Heck if you do and heck if you don't. Waiting to find out their intentions got men killed. <br><br>
I too enjoyed the garbage run when I first got there. The flies and the smell, but it beat burning shitters. <br><br>
I recall my first run garbage run. <br>
From my Diary (copyright 1997).<br><br>
&quot;Dozens of hungry kids, most of them under ten years of age, came rushing toward the rear of the truck. They swarmed over the trash as soon as we threw it out and started to bite, kick and fight among themselves for whatever piece of trash they could scrounge that appeared edible or usable to them. Most were war orphans contending for whatever tit-bits of food they could find.  Some were clearly veterans in this war of hunger, and the spoils of war. They spied out the better morsels of discarded trash, which they quickly scooped up and would later sell for money. Others were shoveling as much of the stuff as they could into small bamboo disks, depositing them at the feet of their smaller siblings and returning to the trash pile for another load.<br>
While we pushed the trash out of the truck, the kids began to climb onto the back of the truck for first pickings of the trash that was visibly more appealing. Some were stuffing globs of mixed food into their mouths that they had dug out of the mess hall barrels. Others were pocketing full, empty and half-empty cans of C-rations. One small boy had gotten so close to the back of the truck that he was being buried alive with the piles of trash we were unloading. <br><br>
The small boy was only about six years old, wearing a brown T-shirt with a Mickey Mouse design barely visible on it. The boy was missing his left ear, two front teeth and his hair was matted and full of lice. I guess Baker and I were thinking the same thing because as we both started to reach down to help the small boy. Lance Corporal Dunning fired a couple of shots into the air. <br><br>
The children scattered, jumping over the sides of the truck, over each other, and scrambling for the safety of the perimeter wire. The young boy emerged from underneath the pile of rubble and both Baker and I pulled him up onto the truck. We then quickly unloaded what trash remained in the truck kicking off the last of it with our feet. I gave the boy the paper Vietnamese currency I had been given when I had arrived in DaNang and we both helped him off the truck. The boy just stood there staring at us wide-eyed his mouth agape. The truck started to move out and immediately, the kids started advancing toward the piles of refuse. As we pulled out, about a dozen boys started kicking and fighting each other for an unopened can of lima beans. I realized then, that I had witnessed both hunger and the fortunes of war.&quot;<br>

